üö≤ Riding a Bike ‚Äî Node Derivatives (30 Truths)
 
1. Grammar (Existence Truth in Action)
‚Ä¢	Phonology √ó Morphology: Are the physical parts present and properly shaped (pedals, chain, wheels)?
o	Virtue: Bike intact.
o	Tilt: Bent part, still usable.
o	Collapse: Missing essential part.
‚Ä¢	Phonology √ó Lexicon: Do you recognize these parts as belonging to ‚Äúbike‚Äù?
o	Virtue: Correctly categorized.
o	Tilt: Confused with trike or scooter, still ridable.
o	Collapse: No recognition, no attempt.
‚Ä¢	Morphology √ó Lexicon: Does the form fit the category?
o	Virtue: Two wheels, a frame.
o	Tilt: Form mismatch (training wheels, trike).
o	Collapse: Form unrideable.

üëâ Crown: The bike is real and ridable.
 
2. Logic (Consequence Truth in Action)
‚Ä¢	Syntax √ó Semantics: Parts in order, and their meaning clear. (Pedals ‚Üí chain ‚Üí wheel).
o	Virtue: System understood.
o	Tilt: Order known but function fuzzy.
o	Collapse: No cause-effect map.
‚Ä¢	Syntax √ó Consequence: Order predicts outcome. (Pedal = forward, brake = stop).
o	Virtue: Reliable prediction.
o	Tilt: Partially right (pedal works, brake misused).
o	Collapse: No effect understood.
‚Ä¢	Semantics √ó Consequence: Meaning verified by result. (Pedals push = wheels turn).
o	Virtue: Meaning matches action.
o	Tilt: Misnamed but works.
o	Collapse: Misunderstood, fails.

üëâ Crown: The bike works logically.
 
3. Rhetoric (Expression Truth in Action)
‚Ä¢	Ethos √ó Pathos: Trust and emotion together. (Teacher inspires courage).
o	Virtue: Rider motivated and confident.
o	Tilt: Trust without feeling, or hype without trust.
o	Collapse: Neither present.
‚Ä¢	Ethos √ó Logos: Trust and reason. (Coach explains persuasively).
o	Virtue: Both strong.
o	Tilt: Good reason but no credibility, or trust without reasoning.
o	Collapse: Neither.
‚Ä¢	Pathos √ó Logos: Feeling supports reasoning. (Excitement drives effort, logic keeps it steady).
o	Virtue: Balanced expression.
o	Tilt: Overhyped or too rational.
o	Collapse: Neither passion nor clarity.

üëâ Crown: Riding is expressed and shared.
 
4. Praxis (Action Truth in Time)
‚Ä¢	Intention √ó Execution: Will and doing aligned. (‚ÄúI will ride‚Äù ‚Üí pedaling).
o	Virtue: Action matches aim.
o	Tilt: Good aim but clumsy execution, or execution without clear aim.
o	Collapse: Neither.
‚Ä¢	Intention √ó Feedback: Will guided by lessons. (‚ÄúI‚Äôll try again differently‚Äù).
o	Virtue: Adjustment builds mastery.
o	Tilt: Aim without correction, or correction without consistent aim.
o	Collapse: Neither.
‚Ä¢	Execution √ó Feedback: Doing creates learning. (Wobble ‚Üí balance improved).
o	Virtue: Practice refines skill.
o	Tilt: Action without learning, or correction without steady effort.
o	Collapse: Neither.

üëâ Crown: Riding is done and improved.
 
5. Presence (Witness Truth in Awareness)
‚Ä¢	Awareness √ó Alignment: Rider senses balance and keeps posture.
o	Virtue: Body-bike synced.
o	Tilt: Awareness without alignment, or alignment without clear perception.
o	Collapse: Neither.
‚Ä¢	Awareness √ó Willpower: Rider feels instability but keeps going.
o	Virtue: Conscious persistence.
o	Tilt: Aware but weak-willed, or blind but stubborn.
o	Collapse: Neither.
‚Ä¢	Alignment √ó Willpower: Posture and resolve aligned.
o	Virtue: Determined, balanced riding.
